TTLEMENT -- tCHAPTER 17 DENDROARCHAEOLOGICAL REPORT ON THE COFFIN FROM THE NABATAEAN BUILT TOMB -- tCHAPTER 18 IRON I AND CHALCOLITHIC/EARLY BRONZE I F AUNA -- tCHAPTER 19 RADIOCARBON DATES -- tPART V CONCLUDING REMARKS -- tCHAPTER 20 MAṢṢEBOTH (STANDING STONES) IN GATES -- tCHAPTER 21 SUMMARY AND CONCLUSIONS -- tADDENDUM LATER EXCAVATIONS IN THE NABATAEAN BUILT TOMB -- tLIST OF LOCI -- tSECTION II THE EARLY ISLAMIC SETTLEMENT -- tPART VI ARCHITECTURAL REMAINS -- tCHAPTER 22 ARCHITECTURE AND STRATIGRAPHY -- tPART VII ARTIFACTS -- tCHAPTER 23 THE POTTERY -- tCHAPTER 24 PERFECTING LOCAL PRODUCTION OF DESERT POTTERY: PETROGRAPHIC ANALYSIS OF EARLY ISLAMIC WARES -- tCHAPTER 25 STONE AND METAL OBJECTS -- tCHAPTER 26 GLASS FINDS -- tCHAPTER 27 THE OSTRACA -- tCHAPTER 28 THE COINS -- tCHAPTER 29 TEXTILES, TEXTILE IMPRESSIONS AND A PLAIT -- tPART VIII ECOFACTS -- tCHAPTER 30 IDENTIFICATION OF DYES -- tCHAPTER 31 ARCHAEOBOTANICAL REMAINS FROM THE EARLY ISLAMIC SITE -- tCHAPTER 32 FAUNAL REMAINS -- tCHAPTER 33 MOLLUSCS -- tPART IX CONCLUDING REMARKS -- tCHAPTER 34 DISCUSSION AND CONCLUSIONS -- tLIST OF LOCI0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis book presents the final report of the excavations at Yotvata, the largest oasis in the Arabah Valley, conducted by the Sonia and Marco Nadler Institute of Archaeology of Tel Aviv University in 1974–1980 under the direction of Dr. Zeʾev Meshel. The report covers two central sites: a fortified Iron I site and an Early Islamic settlement. The Iron I remains consist of an irregular casemate wall surrounding a courtyard. The location of this site suggests that the settlement was established in order to protect the water sources and to overlook and supervise the nearby crossroads. Based on the relative proximity of the site to Timna, it may be concluded that the oasis formed the main source of water and wood for the population involved in copper production in that region.The rich finds uncovered at the Early Islamic settlement—including a large courtyard building and a nearby bathhouse, among other structures—point to habitation from the end of the seventh to the early ninth century CE. The proximity of the settlement to a sophisticated irrigation system (qanat) and the administrative/economic ostraca discovered at the site suggest that it served as the center of an agricultural estate owned by an elite Muslim family. Among the unique finds is a large assemblage of locally produced, handmade pottery, which is thoroughly studied here.The findings from the excavations at the Yotvata oasis have made a major contribution to the study of Early Islamic settlement and material culture in the greater Arabah region and beyond.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Archaeology.2bisacsh  aEarly Islamic settlement history.  aInstitute of Archaeology of Tel Aviv University.  aYotvata excavations.  afortified Iron I site.  amaterial culture in the greater Arabah region.1 aAmar, Zohar, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAmitai-Preiss, Nitzan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAvner, Uzi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAyalon, Etan, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aAyalon, Etan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBar-Yosef Mayer, Daniella E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBen-Shlomo, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBenzaquen, Mordechay, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerman, Ariel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarmi, Israel, econt